narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: We had a lot of thought-provoking discussions in this course that opened my way of thinking to new perspectives.

This class was a great entryway into collegiate writing, with a specific focus on research. I feel that I was well equipped to develop nuanced and complex claims and arguments to enter academic conversations with my writing.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Weekly readings were clearly laid out, as were the due dates on papers. The organization of the course was good.

One of the greatest strengths of this class is its syllabus and the readings it places focus on. Majority of the texts are written by or about people of color and center underrepresented narratives in academia. I felt that the selection of literature was great as someone interested in ethnic studies, history, and race. The professor is another strength of the class. I feel that Professor Baynes-Ross is incredibly knowledgeable and insightful and that I learned so much from her alone. A weakness of the class is its structuring of writing assignments. The first essay was very challenging for me because instructions were not clear and students were expected to do work completely alone and with a quick turn around time to gauge our writing levels. However, I feel that this made it very hard for me to complete the assignment to the best of my ability. The two papers that followed also had an essence of 'do it on your own' and I often felt very lost and unsupported in my writing/research. Sometimes the feedback on my writing wasn't very clear and seemed to lead me in several different directions which was frustrating.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would. It is very helpful for those seeking to improve their writing.
Yes. The course covered broader topics and authors than the typically studied rebellion writers of history. The topics are of a wide range by week which keeps conversation interesting.
I would definitely recommend this course! I felt really engaged--mostly because of the readings which I really enjoyed and feel that I am much more secure in my academic writing abilities.
